<methodology slug="workflow-spec-phase">
  <metadata>
    <tier>solo</tier>
    <group>sdd</group>
    <domain>sdd-planning</domain>
    <summary>Step-by-step procedures for the SDD specification phase: constitutions, specifications, backlog grooming, and roadmapping with human-in-loop checkpoints at section boundaries.</summary>
    <tags>
      <tag>specification</tag>
      <tag>requirements</tag>
      <tag>workflow</tag>
      <tag>sdd</tag>
      <tag>constitution</tag>
    </tags>
    <difficulty>intermediate</difficulty>
    <created>2026-04-26</created>
  </metadata>
  <content>
    <title>Workflow: Specification Phase</title>

    <summary>Step-by-step procedures for the SDD specification phase: writing constitutions (two modes: existing codebase analysis vs. Socratic dialogue for new projects), writing specifications (Brainstorm → Research → Clarify → Draft → Review → Save), backlog grooming with Definition of Ready, and roadmapping with confidence levels (90/70/50%). All workflows have human-in-loop checkpoints at section boundaries.</summary>

    <why>
      <p>Agents writing specs without Socratic dialogue produce assumption-driven requirements that fail AC validation. Without constitution analysis, new code contradicts implicit standards. Without a backlog grooming Definition of Ready, features enter execution with unapproved specs and missing dependencies. The structured procedures enforce incremental validation (show each section, get approval) before proceeding.</p>
    </why>

    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Starting a new feature where requirements are unclear or only partially defined</item>
        <item>Existing codebase needs a constitution — tech decisions are implicit and undocumented</item>
        <item>Backlog grooming session where features need prioritization and DoR verification</item>
        <item>Roadmap needs a reality check against current feature status</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>

    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Feature is a bugfix with a single clear root cause — skip spec, go straight to task</item>
        <item>Requirements fully documented elsewhere (existing PRD) — extract, don't re-elicit</item>
        <item>Constitution already exists and team agrees — skip Mode 1 discovery</item>
        <item>Rapid prototype/spike where requirements will change after seeing output</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>

    <section name="constitution-workflow">
      <p>Procedures for creating constitution.md in two modes: analyzing an existing codebase vs. Socratic dialogue for new projects.</p>

      <section name="mode-1-existing-project">
        <list>
          <item>Step 1 (Detect): read directory layout, CLAUDE.md, README.md, config files (pyproject.toml, package.json, .eslintrc)</item>
          <item>Step 2 (Analyze): identify tech stack, architecture patterns, naming conventions, linter/formatter setup, testing configuration</item>
          <item>Step 3 (Present Findings): "Analysis: 1. Tech: Python 3.11, Django 4.2, PostgreSQL. 2. Architecture: layered (views→services→models). 3. Standards: black + isort + flake8. Does this match? What to change?"</item>
          <item>Step 4 (Draft and Review): incorporate feedback, write constitution.md</item>
        </list>
        <rule>
          <statement>In Mode 1, let codebase analysis lead; do not write standards from memory or training data.</statement>
          <rationale>Agents copy patterns from existing code without checking if those patterns are intentional standards or technical debt. Present findings to the team before committing them as standards. What looks like a convention may be an accident.</rationale>
        </rule>
      </section>

      <section name="mode-2-new-project">
        <list>
          <item>Step 1 (Vision): "Tell me about the project. What problem does it solve?" Apply Five Whys to reach the real need.</item>
          <item>Step 2 (Tech Choices): present A/B/C with pros/cons for backend, database, frontend framework</item>
          <item>Step 3 (Architecture): discuss monolith vs microservices, REST vs GraphQL, ORM vs raw SQL — with trade-offs for this specific project</item>
          <item>Step 4 (Standards): linter, formatter, type hints, testing coverage, CI/CD, git conventions</item>
          <item>Step 5 (Draft): write constitution.md</item>
          <item>Step 6 (Review): validate with team before committing</item>
        </list>
      </section>

      <section name="save-and-setup">
        <list>
          <item>Create .aidocs/ directory structure: backlog/, todo/, in-progress/, done/</item>
          <item>Write constitution.md to .aidocs/constitution.md</item>
          <item>Create CLAUDE.md navigation hub in project folder</item>
        </list>
      </section>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Copying constitution sections from a different project or from training data without validating against the actual codebase.</description>
        <reason>Constitution copied without validation becomes "aspirational" rather than descriptive. When executor agents follow the constitution but the codebase contradicts it, they produce inconsistent code that fails review.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Over-engineering the constitution for a new project by specifying microservices, message queues, and multi-region deployment from day one.</description>
        <reason>Premature architectural complexity locks in decisions that should emerge from actual usage. Start with the simplest architecture that could work; the constitution can be updated when complexity is justified.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>

    <section name="specification-workflow">
      <p>Brainstorm → Research → Clarify → Draft → Review → Save procedure for writing spec.md, with Socratic dialogue techniques and anti-patterns.</p>

      <section name="philosophy">
        <rule>
          <statement>Start every spec session with the problem statement, never the solution; ask "what pain?" before "what feature?"</statement>
          <rationale>Solution-first specs embed implementation assumptions into requirements. Problem-first specs leave design decisions to the design phase. When a spec says "add a button that exports to CSV," it has already made a UI and format decision that belongs in design.md.</rationale>
        </rule>
        <list>
          <item>Intent is source of truth — spec is the main artifact, not a reflection of a prior decision</item>
          <item>Socratic dialogue — user formulates requirements through questions, not monologue</item>
          <item>Incremental validation — show each section, get approval, then continue</item>
        </list>
      </section>

      <section name="phase-1-brainstorming">
        <list>
          <item>Opening: "Tell me about the problem. Who suffers and how?"</item>
          <item>Five Whys: for each answer, ask "Why?" — "Need export" → "Why?" → "Managers ask" → "Why?" → "No access" → Real problem: UX gap</item>
          <item>Alternatives: for each idea, present A/B with pros/cons, ask "Which is closer?"</item>
          <item>Challenge: "Is this needed for v1?", "What if we DON'T do this?", "Does this already exist in the codebase?"</item>
        </list>
        <rule>
          <statement>Ask one question at a time in Socratic dialogue; wait for response before asking the next.</statement>
          <rationale>Agents interpret "Socratic dialogue" as asking multiple questions in a batch then proceeding. Single-question pauses enforce genuine elicitation. Without this, agents hallucinate answers to unanswered questions.</rationale>
        </rule>
      </section>

      <section name="phase-2-3-research-and-clarify">
        <list>
          <item>Phase 2 (Research): grep codebase for similar implementations; share findings: "Found existing export in services.py. Does this affect the approach?"</item>
          <item>Phase 3 (Clarify): user stories workshop — "As {role}, I want {goal}, so that {benefit}. How often? What happens if this fails?"; ask edge cases as questions, never assume</item>
        </list>
      </section>

      <section name="phase-4-draft-section-by-section">
        <list>
          <item>Problem Statement → show → validate: "Is this correct?"</item>
          <item>User Stories with AC → show → validate: "Is this complete?"</item>
          <item>Functional Requirements → show → validate: "Anything redundant?"</item>
          <item>Out of Scope → show → validate: "Agree with boundaries?" (capture while fresh)</item>
        </list>
      </section>

      <section name="phase-5-6-review-and-save">
        <list>
          <item>Phase 5 (Review): verify problem is SMART, user stories follow INVEST, requirements are testable, out-of-scope is explicit; call faion-sdd-reviewer-agent (mode: spec)</item>
          <item>Phase 6 (Save): new feature → .aidocs/features/backlog/{NN}-{feature}/spec.md; existing feature → update spec.md in existing folder</item>
        </list>
      </section>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Agent makes assumptions instead of asking questions when user says "I don't know".</description>
        <reason>"I don't know" is valid input that must be documented as uncertainty, not interpolated. Agents that fill uncertainty with plausible answers produce specs that look complete but contain fabricated requirements.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Writing large blocks of spec without incremental validation.</description>
        <reason>Errors in section 1 propagate to sections 2-8. Show and validate each section before proceeding; fixing a requirement after five dependent sections are written requires rewriting all downstream sections.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>

    <section name="backlog-grooming-and-roadmapping">
      <p>Backlog grooming workflow with Definition of Ready checklist, and roadmapping with confidence levels (90/70/50%).</p>

      <section name="backlog-grooming-workflow">
        <list>
          <item>Step 1: Read roadmap.md and constitution.md</item>
          <item>Step 2: List features by status: in-progress, todo, backlog (P0/P1/P2)</item>
          <item>Step 3: Ask user: "What do you want to do?" — review priorities, take feature, add feature, remove feature, finish grooming</item>
          <item>Step 4: For selected feature — check document completeness</item>
          <item>Step 5: If no spec → run Writing Specifications workflow</item>
          <item>Step 6: If spec approved, no design → run Writing Design Documents workflow</item>
          <item>Step 7: If design approved, no impl-plan → run Writing Implementation Plans workflow</item>
          <item>Step 8: When all artifacts complete → move from backlog/ to todo/</item>
        </list>
      </section>

      <section name="definition-of-ready">
        <rule>
          <statement>A feature is ready to move from backlog to todo only when all DoR criteria are met; features without approved spec or design must remain in backlog.</statement>
          <rationale>Moving features to todo with unapproved artifacts causes executor agents to start implementation against draft requirements, producing code that must be discarded when the spec or design changes.</rationale>
        </rule>
        <list>
          <item>Problem/need is clear and documented</item>
          <item>Acceptance criteria defined (Given/When/Then format)</item>
          <item>Dependencies identified and unblocked</item>
          <item>Feature is small enough for one sprint (or decomposed into multiple features)</item>
          <item>spec.md status: Approved</item>
          <item>design.md status: Approved</item>
          <item>implementation-plan.md status: Approved</item>
          <item>TASK_*.md files created and reviewed</item>
          <item>No blockers outstanding</item>
        </list>
      </section>

      <section name="roadmapping">
        <list>
          <item>When to run: after completing features, when priorities change, weekly/sprint roadmap sync, adding new ideas</item>
          <item>Phase 1 (Analyze): count completed features in done/, count backlog; review milestones</item>
          <item>Phase 2 (Review Priorities): "Are priorities current?" — update MoSCoW if needed</item>
          <item>Phase 3 (Add Features): for each new idea — Socratic dialogue, create backlog/{NN}-{name}/spec.md with problem statement, add to roadmap.md</item>
          <item>Phase 4 (Update Roadmap): Now (90%) detailed/committed, Next (70%) planned/flexible, Later (50%) thematic/vision, Done with highlights</item>
        </list>
        <rule>
          <statement>Roadmap "Later (50%)" items must not get detailed specs prematurely; they should have only a problem statement until promoted to "Next".</statement>
          <rationale>Agents over-specify "Later" items because spec writing is their strength. Over-specified items for distant features create false precision and waste spec effort when priorities change — which they do for 50% confidence items.</rationale>
        </rule>
        <rule>
          <statement>Roadmap confidence levels (90/70/50%) must be explicit; agents over-estimate confidence without this constraint.</statement>
          <rationale>Without explicit confidence levels, all backlog items look equally certain. The 90/70/50% framework forces honest uncertainty quantification and prevents "Now (90%)" items from competing for capacity with speculative "Later (50%)" work.</rationale>
        </rule>
      </section>
    </section>

    <scripts>
      <script path="scripts/backlog-audit.sh" purpose="Print feature status table across all lifecycle stages"/>
    </scripts>

